We can simplify the problem by taking each factor modulo 5 separately.
\begin{align*}
2011 &\equiv 1 \pmod{5} \\
2012 &\equiv 2 \pmod{5} \\
2013 &\equiv 3 \pmod{5} \\
2014 &\equiv 4 \pmod{5}
\end{align*}
Now we can multiply these congruences together modulo 5:
$1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 4 \equiv 24 \equiv \boxed{4} \pmod{5}$.
The answer is: 4

We want to find an integer $x$ such that $11x\equiv 1\pmod{1000}$.
We can use the extended Euclidean algorithm to find the modular inverse.
\begin{align*}
1000 &= 11(90) + 10 \\
11 &= 10(1) + 1
\end{align*}
Working backwards, we have
\begin{align*}
1 &= 11 - 10(1) \\
&= 11 - (1000 - 11(90))(1) \\
&= 11(91) - 1000(1)
\end{align*}
Thus, the modular inverse of $11$ modulo $1000$ is $\boxed{91}$.The answer is: 91

To find the modular inverse of $11$ modulo $1000$, we want to find an integer $x$ such that $11x \equiv 1 \pmod{1000}$.
We can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm to solve this congruence.
First, we write $1000$ as a linear combination of $11$ and $1000$:
\begin{align*}
1000 &= 11 \cdot 90 + 10.
\end{align*}
Then, we write $11$ as a linear combination of $10$ and the remainder from the previous step:
\begin{align*}
11 &= 10 \cdot 1 + 1.
\end{align*}
Next, we work backwards to express $1$ as a linear combination of $10$ and $11$:
\begin{align*}
1 &= 11 - 10 \cdot 1 \\
&= 11 - (1000 - 11 \cdot 90) \cdot 1 \\
&= 11 - 1000 + 11 \cdot 90 \\
&= 11 \cdot 91 - 1000.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the modular inverse of $11$ modulo $1000$ is $91$.
So the answer is $\boxed{91}$.The answer is: 91

